fb0be393-ce49-41f5-a84a-727b9f101bb1.1984041f-c5a3-42ac-a270-0a9c0358e8f3.description=
 
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable. 
    trimSpaces - If set on "true" then all the whitespaces will be removed from the value stored. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false

Returns\: 
    The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable with all whitespaces removed.

Responses\:
    isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
    notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned. 

Notes\: 
    1. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "true" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "isNull". 
    2. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "false" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "notNull". 
    3. If any other value than "true" or "false" is passed on "trimSpaces" input then the default value (false) will be used.

fb0be393-ce49-41f5-a84a-727b9f101bb1.34ef2416-7f3b-4718-b1f4-5e586b732e0e.transition.description=no more fb0be393-ce49-41f5-a84a-727b9f101bb1.3aa74d59-3423-40ff-b53c-f6f869e6e43b.description=
Accepts an object in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON) and
returns a value for the specified key.

The JSON format encodes objects as a set of unordered key/value pairs, which is
similar to a structure or map in other programming languages.  For example,
   { "city" \: "Palo Alto", 
     "state" \: "CA" }
is an object with two elements one with the name "city" having the value "Palo
Alto", and the other being the name "state" with the value "CA". This operation would 
return "Palo Alto" if user enters "city" as a key.

If the input object contains JSON array, array index can be used in the key input. For example, 
{ "location"\: [
      {"city"\: "Roseville", "country"\: "United States"},
      {"city"\: "Cluj", "country"\: "Romania"},
      {"city"\: "Yehud", "country"\: "Israel"}]    
}
The operation would return "Roseville" if user enters "location[0].city" as a key.

JavaScript objects are useful for representing structured data, and are
especially when used within an array.  For example, an operation that retrieves
a set of incidents from an external system may return the entire list in one
array of incident objects.  The description of the enclosing folder,
/Library/Utility Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and
the JSON format is described completely at http\://www.json.org.

Inputs

   object
      The JavaScript object.  
      The operation will return a failure if it is not a JavaScript object.

   key
      The key in the object to get the value of.

Responses

   success
      The value was successfully returned for the specified key. 

   failure
      There was some error in processing the object, most likely because the
      object is not in valid JavaScript Object Notation or the specified key does not exist in the object.  
      You may wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose problems with
      JavaScript Object Notation.

Outputs

   The primary output will be the value for the specified key in the object.

Note

    If the value in JSON object is in scientific notation, the returned output will be converted to an equivalent decimal number. Ex, 2.9e+1 will be converted to 29.

This operation adds a flow variable to the local context. The variable is available in the current flow and its child flows.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The name of the flow variable to add.
    myValue - The value to assign to the flow variable.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of "myValue" input field.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.

Note\:
   If a flow variable with the same name already exists, its value will be overwritten.
fb0be393-ce49-41f5-a84a-727b9f101bb1.440f37a5-0e4e-4d66-89cc-674aabfa8966.description=This operation iterates through a string that contains an array in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON). Each time this operation is called, it places the value of the current array element into the "returnResult" output and advances the iterator to the next array element. The JSON format is used to encode arrays and other values using JavaScript notation. For arrays, this means that the values need to be enclosed by square brackets, and each element in the array can be a string (enclosed by quotes), a number, true, false, null, or nested array or object. Commas are always used as delimiters between array elements, and they can also appear within string elements. The benefits of JavaScript arrays are that delimiters are fixed and cannot be confused with data, and that complex nesting of arrays and objects are supported. The description of the enclosing folder, /Library/Utility Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and the JSON format is described completely at http\://www.json.org. Inputs\: array - The JavaScript array that will be iterated through. A normal OO list is NOT a JavaScript array. Examples\: For example, the following is a simple JSON array\: [ "cat", "dog", "horse" ] The equivalent OO list (that is not a JavaScript array) is\: cat,dog,horse Results\: returnResult - This is the primary output and contains the current array element or an exception message if something went wrong. When incorporating this operation into a flow, you should assign a meaningful result value from this field. Responses\: has more - The iterator has not yet reached the end of the array. The "returnResult" output will be populated with the value of the current element in the array, and the iterator will advance to the next element in the array. no more - The iterator has reached the end of the array, and there is no more data to return. The iterator will become undefined after this call, which basically will reset it so that if called again, this operation will begin another iteration at the beginning of the array. failure - There was some error in iterating through the list, and the "returnResult" output will contain information about the error. This will occur if the input array is not a valid JavaScript array. You may wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose problems with JavaScript Object Notation. Notes\: 1. Modifying the contents of the array during iteration is not supported unless the iteration has finished. 2. The operation supports iterating through nested arrays. fb0be393-ce49-41f5-a84a-727b9f101bb1.55fbf5cd-443a-49ed-9cbf-f0fc226a012f.transition.description=lesser than 0 fb0be393-ce49-41f5-a84a-727b9f101bb1.56a4795e-23b2-4782-8b0f-3cd3724e7787.description=
This operation does not do anything. It can be used to filter flow variables by defining them as inputs and filtering them in the Results tab.

Inputs\:
    field1 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field2 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field3 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field4 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of  "field1" as it was specified at input or when filtered. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
fb0be393-ce49-41f5-a84a-727b9f101bb1.633ffd24-90d9-4d46-8c6a-568fa055b9a2.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);
